Total number of words (antal ord) = 51
Total number of letters = 8 + 13 + 3 + 4 + 3 + 5 + 4 + 3 + 5 + 4 + 3 + 8 + 3 + 3 + 6 + 3 + 6 + 9 + 3 + 5 + 6 + 1 + 7 + 8 + 12 + 8 + 3 + 10 + 10 + 3 + 2 + 11 + 3 + 8 + 3 + 3 + 12 + 17 + 9 + 10 + 2 + 8 + 13 + 3 + 19 + 3 + 8 + 11 + 10 + 7 = 281
Average number of letters per word (ordlängd) = total number of letters / total number of words = 281 / 51 ≈ 5.51

Total number of sentences (antal meningar) = 3

Now we can calculate the LIX score:
LIX = ( 5.51 * 100 ) / 51 + ( 5.51 * 100 ) / 3
LIX = 108.039 + 183.67
LIX ≈ 291.709 

However, the second part of the formula ((ordlängd * 100) / antal meningar) appears to have been interpreted incorrectly in our original calculation. The correct formula is meant to calculate the percentage of long words in the given text, and then multiply it by the average number of letters per word divided by the average number of words per sentence. However, the original provided calculation seems also somewhat common but appears harder to understand as the value then is strongly risen by lots. 

Applying the correct calculation LIX = ( avg # of letters in a word ) + ( % of long words ) we first must define a "long word" - It is often defined in this model as the words longer than 6 letters. Taking the above given